<tr><td align="left" valign="bottom" width="98%"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/toptab.gif" width="98" height="10" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td><td align="left" valign="bottom" width="22">&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td bgcolor="#3F403F" width="98%" class="cheader"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></td><td bgcolor="3F403F" valign="top" align="right" width="22"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/topcorner.gif" width="23" height="22" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" align="right"></td></tr>
<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> Brandon Schele - Player Created V9 Card<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.68)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=175'>Scott "CRingwell" Lingrell</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=175&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 17, 2005</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Mon Mothma <br />
Power 3 Ability 4 Politics 5 <br />
Deploy 2 Forfeit 8 <br />
Agendas: order, peace. Game text may not be canceled. Once per game, may V any one battleground. Once per turn, may use 1 Force to add or subtract Mon Mothma’s ability to or from any Epic Event destiny draw. The Emperor may not target characters with politics here. <br />
<br />
Let&#39;s start off with the reasoning as to why I chose Mon Mothma to virtualize. Back when Endor was released, she was the only character I could pull from packs, which was annoying considering I already had her from the second anthology, and she isn&#39;t exactly something you wanted 4 or 5 of at the time. Additionally, she&#39;s pullable by Strike Planning, so you can reliably get her first turn in games where she is crucial. Also she&#39;s a senator (from the glossary supplement), which is good because I wanted to be able to make another control-type deck(like HD and TRM) for the Light Side good again. <br />
<br />
The Light Side was also pretty terrible post virtual set 8, with Throne Room Mains being about the only Light Side deck that could win consistently (well, there were others, just not as strong and usually had bad matchups with something). Therefore, the Light Side needed the most help, and that influenced me to make a Light Side card. So essentially, she was the perfect character to virtualize in my opinion. <br />
<br />
I started off by increasing her power and ability, because she is the leader of the republic after all. She should at least be able to draw destiny. The deploy decrease was to account for Ability, Ability, Ability(V) (and Civil Disorder(V) as well) increasing her deploy by 2, so it balances out fairly well. She got Politics because she is a senator and doesn&#39;t get a politics bonus from the objective, so politics of her own were a must. <br />
<br />
As for the lines of text, I&#39;ll start with the deck specific ones. Agendas: order, peace. Game text may not be canceled. The Emperor may not target characters with politics here. Both of these lines are obviously for LS Senate, so her game text doesn&#39;t disappear due to the objective and The Emperor (V) can no longer lay waste to all of your senators, especially since the LS is short on them to start in comparison to the Dark Side. I gave her agendas, since all senators have them, and Peace and Order make sense for the leader of the Republic. She&#39;ll allow Light Side Senate to be played again, but the Senate player will either be forced to start Strike Planning to get her out right away, or rely on pulling her with Might of The Republic and hoping she&#39;s out in time to stop The Emperor (V) from dismantling the senate. <br />
<br />
Once per game, may / any one battleground. This line is meant to help ALL Light Side decks. On top of being a fairly reliable character with a great forfeit, she can also help boost your activation. The Light Side&#39;s biggest problem was finding a way to get out the battlegrounds to force drain at, and this solves it. All Light Side decks now have a reliable way to pull that extra battleground so they can cause damage. This text alone lets her fit in 95% of Light Side decks. <br />
<br />
And now for the most unique part of her text, the one that helps some Light Side decks and slows down some Dark Side decks: Once per turn, may use 1 Force to add or subtract Mon Mothma’s ability to or from any Epic Event destiny draw. This part allows her to add to draws for Attack Run and Deactivate The Shield Generator, the latter of which really needed help since it requires a draw of >12 as it is, with only getting small bonuses from other cards. <br />
<br />
The subtract from an Epic Event destiny draw line is mainly to slow down Walkers, the least interactive Dark deck there is to me. The deck does nothing but pull every card it needs to set up, and gets pretty much an auto-flip just with those pullable cards, which I have never agreed with. Subtracting 4 from their attempt to blow the Hoth Shield slows them down, and in some cases, forces them to deploy and move to the 3rd Marker before being able to blow up the Hoth Shield with a lower destiny. This gives the Light Side a fighting chance to set up before Walkers starts causing insane amounts of damage, or go and fight Walkers to possibly prevent blowing the Hoth Shields all together. <br />
<br />
And yes, it also subtracts from Epic Duel and Commence Primary Ignition. And before you start freaking out about Lightsaber Combat, keep in mind that the destinies are drawn using the Objective, not the Epic Event, and therefore Mon Mothma cannot add or subtract from it. <br />
<br />
So there you have it, a new character for the Light Side that is pullable in any deck you need her first turn, or just included to be a solid character anyway as a viable counter to certain deck types. I feel like she single-handedly helps the Light Side enough to be competitive, which was my goal when creating her. <br />
<br />
